\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The report of the first evaluator highlighted the following shortcomings\'3A\line Large parts of the application are a cut and paste job from other programmes submitted for accreditation. \line The evaluator stated that the title of the programme\'3A Diploma in Fashion Design \'26 Retail Buying is misleading to prospective applicants. It is necessary to first learn the fundamentals of Fashion Design before specializing in Fashion Retail Buying. \line The programme claims to promote entrepreneur values but fails to include any entrepreneurial knowledge\'2C skills and values. Employability on completion of the programmes will be difficult considering the design of the curriculum. \line This qualification FD\'26RB will not articulate with Clothing Management \'28specialist technician within the clothing industry\'29\'2C Business Management nor Fashion Design of state-run institutions as it lack the rigour and structure that is required of these programmes. \line The admission policy included is not specific to Fashion Design \'26 Retail Buying. A selection procedure based solely on matriculation results may further disadvantage students who do not have an aptitude for a programme in fashion retailing. \line The institution does not have the required number of staff with the necessary qualifications and experience across the various sites to offer the programme. \line The lack of information provided in terms of facilities\'2C may be indicative of a lack of the required facilities to offer a programme of this nature.\line \line The second evaluator indicated that all criteria \'28with the exception of Criterion 6\'29 are in need of improvement. The evaluator noted that in a number of sections the on-line narrative is poorly constructed\'2C deficient and too brief to allow for evidence-based evaluation to take place. The author\'2Fs frequently by-pass or ignore important accreditation criteria focusing attention and responses instead on the on-line questions only. The overall impression created is one of a lack of professionalism and attention to important detail as well as an inability to engage with the specific knowledge project implicated in this candidacy accreditation application. The overall \'E2\'80\'98read\'E2\'80\'99 provides very broad and general information associated with the institution\'E2\'80\'99s existing mission\'2C objectives and strategies. Very little effort has been made to provide an appropriate contextualization of these broad descriptions for the proposed programme. Some of the concerns raised by the second evaluator include\'3A\line The proposed programme exceeds the total permissible NQF level 5 credits for a Diploma programme thus rendering the programme not aligned with the HEQF. The computations of the credits and the credit NQF Levels do not concur with the on-line submission and are also not aligned to the SAQA qualification submission.\line There is no evidence that the learning programme and the teaching and learning strategy \'28and supporting methods\'29 have been explicitly conceptualised in relation to the specific requirements of a combined vocational programme \'28populated with procedural craft knowledge\'29 and a 4th generation professional programme \'28populated by principles and theories relating to the world of-fashion-merchandising-work\'29. There is therefore no clear evidence of the underpinning philosophy of the programme design. The narrative on the competences developed in the programme is very poorly constructed and provides no useful insight or understanding of the programme in relation to the NQF Levels. The vocational and or professional experience of the majority of the educators is not available. It is unclear whether the programme was designed by qualified and experienced staff and it is unclear in the submission how\'2C and to what extent\'2C the full-time staff members recorded as part of Criterion 3 were involved in the programme development and design. \line The percentage of learning time needs to be reviewed and corrected. It is not possible that experiential learning or work-based learning can constitute 25\'25 of the learning time give that the Work Integrated Learning module\'2C comprising 30 \'28of 375\'29 credits\'2C represents only 8\'25 of the learning time. \line \line The admission and matriculation exemption policies and practices articulated in the on-line submission violate the institution\'E2\'80\'99s policy document in this regard and do not fully comply with the minimum admission requirements specified in the Higher Education Qualifications Framework \'28Government Gazette Vol. 508\'2C No. 30353\'2C 5 October 2007\'29.\line It is unclear whether the staff indicated for each site will take responsibility for all or most programme courses. Reference is made to part-time staff and subsequent allocations of staff to programme modules but it is not clear how this mechanism will be operationalised in relation to the full teaching and learning strategy for the proposed programme.\line \line No useful details are available to allow for judgment as to whether administrative\'2C technical and academic development support staff members are adequately qualified for their duties. \line \line The library resources listed for the programme are inadequate. \line \line In the light of the multiplicity of concerns raised\'2C the Directorate cannot support the second evaluator\'27s recommendation of accreditation with conditions\'2C but rather support the first evaluator in not recommending accreditation.\line \cell \pard 

